## Questions are part of learning

I have many questions about life and my experiences. These questions led me to actively participating in learning by doing personal research and finding people who have the same interests and may have the same questions. When interesting questions are brought up, we would try to get through it by discussing several factors that may lead to an answer. Questions are part of the learning process. When people already have basic understanding of the topic and that research was done before a question was asked, the questions that emerge could possibly introduce new ideas that were not brought up before -- and this is what makes learning fun.

I’ve had people ask me about topics that could be easily Googled. Sometimes I feel that they are wasting my time on purpose. When the answer to a question can be answered by resources on the internet or materials provided in a class, that’s when people have to start paying attention to what is in front of them. We have to be proactive in our learning process instead of relying on others to do the work for us and show that we have done the work as well before asking the question. This is what makes a “smart question.” Eric Raymond wrote a guide on [How To Ask Questions The Smart Way](http://www.catb.org/esr/faqs/smart-questions.html#easyreply). He talks about writing a question that has to be accessible, descriptive, and explicit, so that the question also helps others. 

## What is a smart question and what is not...

An example of a non-smart question is [Android development .. can anyone solve this problem](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65951258/android-development-can-anyone-solve-this-problem). The author of the question provided a screenshot of their work and does not provide other information about the project besides it being an Android development. The author does not get close to Raymond's standards of what a smart question is. For one, the question does not provide a specific subject header and only asks for help. The description of the question only has “Can anyone help in solving this exception” and it isn’t even written as a complete sentence. There are no specific questions, goals, nor information about the project that was asked. With questions like these, it makes it harder for volunteers to answer questions because there is not much information that is provided.

An example of a smart question is [pandas: split values and join across columns](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65951438/pandas-split-values-and-join-across-columns). The author of the question decided to make his goal as their header and even provided a sample of the problem and goal in their description. The author wrote in proper grammar. The provides a line of code in which they were able to find a step closer to the goal. They have a short sample of how the code would look like in pure Python and the author clarifies that they are working with Pandas. This post would pass most, if not all of Raymond's standards of asking smart questions.

## Conclusion

Learning how to ask smart questions is beneficial for a programmer. It allows them to think about and improve their learning process. Learning how to ask smart questions also makes people respect one enough to voluntarily answer their questions. By learning to ask smart questions, not only do you benefit from it, but everyone else who found themselves at your place will also benefit.
